    {
      "leftTitle": "Step 3",
      "rightTitle": "Collapse the Delta",
      "left": [
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "Use the delta identity to evaluate the theta integral at the locked phase selected by the constraint. The important point is that the delta fixes the combination theta minus psi, not theta by itself."
        },
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "\\int f(\\theta)\\,\\delta(\\theta-\\theta_*)\\,d\\theta = f(\\theta_*)",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "For the locked term, omega is treated as fixed while the theta integral is collapsed."
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "Because this delta is being evaluated on a finite locked interval, there is an extra assumption built into the step: the selected phase must actually fall inside the allowed theta window. If it does not, the theta integral contributes zero rather than the sampled value of the integrand."
        },
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "f(\\theta,\\omega)=e^{i(\\theta-\\psi)}g(\\omega)",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "\\theta_*(\\omega)=\\psi+\\sin^{-1}\\!\\left(\\frac{\\omega}{Kr}\\right)",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "So the delta piece in Eq. 10 plays the role of delta of theta minus theta star, and the rest of the locked integrand plays the role of f. When the delta fires, it enforces theta minus psi equals sine inverse of omega over K r."
        },
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "\\int e^{i(\\theta-\\psi)}g(\\omega)\\,\\delta\\!\\left[\\theta-\\psi-\\sin^{-1}\\!\\left(\\frac{\\omega}{Kr}\\right)\\right] d\\theta = e^{i(\\theta_*-\\psi)}g(\\omega)",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "The theta integral disappears, but the omega integral remains. Substituting theta star equals psi plus sine inverse of omega over K r gives theta star minus psi equals sine inverse of omega over K r, so the psi terms cancel inside the exponent."
        },
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "\\theta_*(\\omega)-\\psi = \\left(\\psi+\\sin^{-1}\\!\\left(\\frac{\\omega}{Kr}\\right)\\right)-\\psi",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "= \\sin^{-1}\\!\\left(\\frac{\\omega}{Kr}\\right)",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "e^{i(\\theta_*-\\psi)} = e^{i\\sin^{-1}(\\omega/Kr)}",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "An equivalent shortcut is to substitute the selected locked phase directly back into f instead of looking only at the exponent."
        },
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "f(\\theta_*(\\omega),\\omega) = e^{i(\\theta_*(\\omega)-\\psi)}g(\\omega)",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "= e^{i\\left(\\psi+\\sin^{-1}\\!\\left(\\frac{\\omega}{Kr}\\right)-\\psi\\right)}g(\\omega)",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "= e^{i\\sin^{-1}(\\omega/Kr)}g(\\omega)",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "You can now substitute that reduced theta integral back into the full locked term before changing the omega bounds. At that stage the omega integral is still written over the original full line, but only the locked region contributes."
        },
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "I(\\omega)=\\int_{-\\pi/2}^{\\pi/2} e^{i(\\theta-\\psi)}\\,\\delta\\!\\left(\\theta-\\psi-\\sin^{-1}\\!\\left(\\frac{\\omega}{Kr}\\right)\\right)\\,d\\theta",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "=\\begin{cases}e^{i\\sin^{-1}(\\omega/Kr)},& -\\frac{\\pi}{2}\\le \\theta_*(\\omega)-\\psi\\le \\frac{\\pi}{2},\\\\ 0,& \\text{otherwise,}\\end{cases}",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "= e^{i\\sin^{-1}(\\omega/Kr)}\\,\\mathbf{1}_{|\\omega|\\le Kr}",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "This is why straight substitution by itself is incomplete. The sampled value is correct only on the support selected by the finite interval, and that support is what turns into the indicator and then into the new omega bounds."
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "Here bold 1 is the indicator function for the locked region: it equals 1 when the condition below holds, and 0 otherwise."
        },
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "\\mathbf{1}_{|\\omega|\\le Kr}=\\begin{cases}1,& |\\omega|\\le Kr,\\\\ 0,& |\\omega|>Kr.\\end{cases}",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "r = \\int_{-\\infty}^{+\\infty} I(\\omega)\\,g(\\omega)\\,d\\omega",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "= \\int_{-\\infty}^{+\\infty} e^{i\\sin^{-1}(\\omega/Kr)}\\,\\mathbf{1}_{|\\omega|\\le Kr}\\,g(\\omega)\\,d\\omega",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "The new omega bounds come from the old locked phase bounds. The delta-selected phase must still lie inside the allowed locked interval."
        },
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "-\\frac{\\pi}{2} \\le \\theta_* - \\psi \\le \\frac{\\pi}{2}",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "-\\frac{\\pi}{2} \\le \\sin^{-1}\\!\\left(\\frac{\\omega}{Kr}\\right) \\le \\frac{\\pi}{2} \\iff -1 \\le \\frac{\\omega}{Kr} \\le 1",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "\\iff -Kr \\le \\omega \\le Kr",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "So only frequencies whose locked phase lands inside that interval survive the theta integration. That is why the remaining omega integral runs from minus K r to K r."
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "Now expand the sampled phase factor with Euler's formula instead of dropping it by hand."
        },
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "e^{i\\sin^{-1}(\\omega/Kr)} = \\cos\\!\\left(\\sin^{-1}\\!\\left(\\frac{\\omega}{Kr}\\right)\\right) + i\\sin\\!\\left(\\sin^{-1}\\!\\left(\\frac{\\omega}{Kr}\\right)\\right)",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "= \\sqrt{1-\\left(\\frac{\\omega}{Kr}\\right)^2} + i\\,\\frac{\\omega}{Kr}",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "r = \\int_{-Kr}^{Kr}\\!\\left[\\sqrt{1-\\left(\\frac{\\omega}{Kr}\\right)^2} + i\\,\\frac{\\omega}{Kr}\\right] g(\\omega)\\,d\\omega",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "Here odd in omega means the function changes sign when omega is replaced by minus omega: f of minus omega equals minus f of omega. Because g of omega is symmetric, g of minus omega equals g of omega, while omega over K r changes sign. So the imaginary part i times omega over K r times g of omega is an odd integrand.",
          "visualizationLabel": "Open cancellation visualization",
          "visualizationFrame": {
            "mode": "plugin",
            "pluginId": "kuramoto_symmetry_cancellation",
            "name": "Kuramoto Symmetry Cancellation",
            "captureId": "kuramoto-sim"
          }
        },
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "\\left(\\frac{-\\omega}{Kr}\\right) g(-\\omega) = -\\left(\\frac{\\omega}{Kr}\\right) g(\\omega)",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "Integrating an odd function over the symmetric interval from minus K r to K r gives zero, because the contribution at minus omega cancels the contribution at plus omega. Only the real cosine piece survives."
        },
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "r = \\int_{-Kr}^{Kr} \\sqrt{1-\\left(\\frac{\\omega}{Kr}\\right)^2}\\,g(\\omega)\\,d\\omega",
          "displayMode": true
        }
      ],
