    {
      "leftTitle": "Step 4",
      "rightTitle": "Eq. 11",
      "left": [
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "Now change variables to the phase variable used in Eq. 11."
        },
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "\\omega = Kr\\sin \\theta, \\qquad d\\omega = Kr\\cos \\theta\\,d\\theta",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "The old omega bounds must now be rewritten in theta. On the locked branch, sine is one-to-one, so map the endpoints directly: omega equals minus K r gives theta equals minus pi over 2, and omega equals K r gives theta equals pi over 2."
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "The intuition is that on the locked branch theta stays between minus pi over 2 and pi over 2, and over exactly that interval sine runs from minus 1 to plus 1. So multiplying by K r makes omega run from minus K r to plus K r. Reaching the endpoint omega equals K r means sine theta must equal 1, which on this branch happens at theta equals pi over 2."
        },
        {
          "kind": "math",
          "latex": "\\omega=-Kr \\iff \\theta=-\\frac{\\pi}{2}, \\qquad \\omega=Kr \\iff \\theta=\\frac{\\pi}{2}",
          "displayMode": true
        },
        {
          "kind": "text",
          "value": "The square-root factor becomes a second cosine factor, so the integrand turns into the cosine-squared weight in Eq. 11."
        }
      ],
